In React, when you pass an inline object as a prop to a component, it triggers a re-render because React compares the new object with the previous one using reference equality. If the objects are not the same instance (i.e., they have different memory addresses), React considers them different and schedules a re-render.

To prevent this behavior and ensure that the component only re-renders when the actual data changes, you can use the `useMemo` hook from React. The `useMemo` hook allows you to memoize expensive computations or complex operations so they are only recalculated when their dependencies change.

Here's an example of how to use `useMemo` to prevent a component from re-rendering unnecessarily:

```jsx
import React, { useMemo } from 'react';

const MyComponent = ({ data }) => {
  // Use useMemo to memoize the expensive computation
  const computedValue = useMemo(() => {
    // Perform some expensive operation on data
    return data.map(item => item * 2);
  }, [data]); // Only recompute if data changes

  return (
    <div>
      {computedValue}
    </div>
  );
};

export default MyComponent;
```

In this example, the `useMemo` hook is used to memoize the `computedValue`. The `computedValue` is a new array that is created by mapping each item in the `data` array to its double. The dependency array `[data]` ensures that the computation is only re-run when the `data` prop changes.

